SIMPLE: tattle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tattle
<hw>Tat"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Tattled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tattling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Akin to OE.
<ets>tateren</ets>, LG. <ets>tateln</ets>, D. <ets>tateren</ets> to
stammer, and perhaps to E. <ets>titter</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
prate; to talk idly; to use many words with little meaning; to
chat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>tattling</qex> quality of age, which is always
narrative.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To tell tales; to communicate secrets; to be a
talebearer; <as>as, a <ex>tattling</ex> girl</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tattle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tattle
<hw>Tat"tle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Idle talk or chat; trifling talk;
prate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] told the <qex>tattle</qex> of the day.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tattler</ent>⟦br⟧
